# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atkinson-cycle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:atkinson-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:atkinson-cycle/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] "**An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction**" is a scientific paper by Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford, which was published in the Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society in 1798.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] The paper provided a substantial challenge to established theories of heat, and began the 19th century revolution in thermodynamics.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was an opponent of the caloric theory of heat which held that heat is a fluid that could be neither created nor destroyed.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He had further developed the view that all gases and liquids are absolute non-conductors of heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] His views were out of step with the accepted science of the time and the latter theory had particularly been attacked by John Dalton and John Leslie.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was heavily influenced by the argument from design and it is likely that he wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Though Rumford was to come to associate heat with motion, there is no evidence that he was committed to the kinetic theory or the principle of *vis viva*.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] In his 1798 paper, Rumford acknowledged that he had predecessors in the notion that heat was a form of motion.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Those predecessors included Francis Bacon, Robert Boyle, Robert Hooke, John Locke, and Henry Cavendish.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring out cannon barrels at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] At that time, cannons were cast at the foundry with an extra section of metal forward of what would become the muzzle, and this section was removed and discarded later in the manufacturing process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford took an unfinished cannon and modified this section to allow it to be enclosed by a watertight box while a blunted boring tool was used on it.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He showed that water in this box could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours, and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining were the same.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford also argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He contended that the only thing communicated to the barrel was motion.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford made no attempt to further quantify the heat generated or to measure the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Most established scientists, such as William Henry, as well as Thomas Thomson, believed that there was enough uncertainty in the caloric theory to allow its adaptation to account for the new results.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] It had certainly proved robust and adaptable up to that time.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Furthermore, Thomson, Jöns Jakob Berzelius, and Antoine César Becquerel observed that electricity could be indefinitely generated by friction.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] No educated scientist of the time was willing to hold that electricity was not a fluid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Ultimately, Rumford's claim of the "inexhaustible" supply of heat was a reckless extrapolation from the study.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Charles Haldat made some penetrating criticisms of the reproducibility of Rumford's results and it is possible to see the whole experiment as somewhat tendentious.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] However, the experiment inspired the work of James Prescott Joule in the 1840s.
[src:atkinson-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Joule's more exact measurements were pivotal in establishing the kinetic theory at the expense of caloric.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The **Atkinson-cycle engine** is a type of internal combustion engine invented by James Atkinson in 1882.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Atkinson cycle is designed to provide efficiency at the expense of power density.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] A variation of this approach is used in some modern automobile engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] While originally seen exclusively in hybrid electric applications such as the earlier-generation Toyota Prius, later hybrids and some non-hybrid vehicles now feature engines with variable valve timing.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Variable valve timing can run in the Atkinson cycle as a part-time operating regimen, giving good economy while running in Atkinson cycle mode, and conventional power density when running in conventional Otto cycle mode.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson produced three different designs that had a short compression stroke and a longer expansion stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The first Atkinson-cycle engine, the *differential engine*, used opposed pistons.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The second and best-known design was the *cycle engine*, which used an over-center arm to create four piston strokes in one crankshaft revolution.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This unusual reciprocating engine had the intake, compression, power, and exhaust strokes of the four-stroke cycle in a single turn of the crankshaft, and was designed to avoid infringing certain patents covering Otto-cycle engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's third and final engine, the *utilite engine*, operated much like a two-stroke engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Apart from the features implemented to avoid Otto patents, the truly unique Atkinson's design is that the engines have an expansion stroke that is longer than the compression stroke, and by this method the engine achieves greater thermal efficiency than a traditional piston engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's engines were produced by the British Gas Engine Company and also licensed to other overseas manufacturers.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Many modern engines now use a crankshaft center-line offset from the cylinder center-line (making them desaxe engines) and/or unconventional valve timing to produce the effect of a shorter compression stroke/longer power stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Miller applied this technique to the four-stroke engine, so it is sometimes referred as the Atkinson/Miller cycle, US patent 2817322 dated Dec 24, 1957.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In 1888, Charon filed a French patent and displayed an engine at the Paris Exhibition in 1889.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Charon gas engine (four-stroke) used a similar cycle to Miller, but without a supercharger.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] It is referred to as the "Charon cycle".
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Hugo Güldner argued in his 1914 book that Körting was the first firm to build a gas engine with a short compression stroke and a longer expansion phase in 1891, based on a design first proposed by Otto Köhler in 1887.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This engine also had an engine-load dependent valve train which increased the intake and compression stroke with increasing engine load.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] On the other hand, the compression was decreasing at low and medium loads, which ultimately reduced the efficiency.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Roy Fedden, at Bristol, tested an arrangement in the Bristol Jupiter IV engine in 1928, with variable retard timing allowing part of the charge to be blown back into the intake manifold, in order to have sustainable reduced operation pressures during takeoff.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Modern engine designers are realizing the potential fuel-efficiency improvements the Atkinson-type cycle can provide.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The first implementation of the Atkinson cycle was in 1882; unlike later versions, it was arranged as an opposed-piston engine, the Atkinson differential engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Thus, in each revolution, one piston provided a compression stroke and a power stroke, and then the other piston provided an exhaust stroke and a charging stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The next engine designed by Atkinson in 1887 was named the "Cycle Engine" This engine used poppet valves, a cam, and an over-center arm to produce four piston strokes for every revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The intake and compression strokes were significantly shorter than the expansion and exhaust strokes.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The "Cycle" engines were produced and sold for several years by the British Engine Company.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson also licensed production to other manufacturers.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Sizes ranged from a few up to 100 horsepower.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's third design was named the "Utilite Engine".
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's "Cycle" engine was efficient; however, its linkage was difficult to balance for high speed operation.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson realized an improvement was needed to make his cycle more applicable as a higher-speed engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Utilite operates much like a standard two-stroke except that the exhaust port is located at about the middle of the stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] During the expansion/power stroke, a cam-operated valve (which remains closed until the piston nears the end of the stroke) prevents pressure from escaping as the piston moves past the exhaust port.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The exhaust valve is opened near the bottom of the stroke; it remains open as the piston heads back toward compression, letting fresh air charge the cylinder and exhaust escape until the port is covered by the piston.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] After the exhaust port is covered the piston begins to compress the remaining air in the cylinder.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] A small piston fuel pump injects liquid during compression.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The ignition source was likely a hot tube as in Atkinson's other engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This design resulted in a two-stroke engine with a short compression and longer expansion stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Utilite Engine tested as even more efficient than Atkinson's previous "differential" and "cycle" designs.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Very few were produced, and none are known to survive.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] No US patent for the Utilite Engine is known.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In the late 20th century, the term "Atkinson cycle" began to be used to describe a modified Otto-cycle engine—in which the intake valve is held open longer than normal, allowing a reverse flow of intake air into the intake manifold.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This "simulated" Atkinson cycle is most notably used in the Toyota 1NZ-FXE engine from the early Prius and the Toyota Dynamic Force engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The effective compression ratio is reduced—for the time the air is escaping the cylinder freely rather than being compressed—but the *expansion* ratio is unchanged (i.e., the compression ratio is smaller than the expansion ratio).
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The goal of the modern Atkinson cycle is to make the pressure in the combustion chamber at the end of the power stroke equal to atmospheric pressure.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] When this occurs, all available energy has been obtained from the combustion process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] For any given portion of air, the greater expansion ratio converts more energy from heat to useful mechanical energy—meaning the engine is more efficient.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The disadvantage of the four-stroke Atkinson-cycle engine versus the more common Otto-cycle engine is reduced power density.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Due to a smaller portion of the compression stroke being devoted to compressing the intake air, an Atkinson-cycle engine does not take in as much air as would a similarly designed and sized Otto-cycle engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Four-stroke engines of this type that use the same type of intake valve motion but also utilize forced induction to make up for the loss of power density are known as Miller-cycle engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Atkinson cycle can be used in a rotary engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In this configuration, an increase in both power and efficiency can be achieved when compared to the Otto cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This type of engine retains the one power phase per revolution, together with the different compression and expansion volumes of the original Atkinson cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Exhaust gases are expelled from the engine by compressed-air scavenging.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This modification of the Atkinson cycle allows the use of alternative fuels such as diesel and hydrogen.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Disadvantages of this design include the requirement that rotor tips seal very tightly on the outer housing wall and the mechanical losses suffered through friction between rapidly oscillating parts of irregular shape.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] See *§ External links* below for more information.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] While a modified Otto-cycle piston engine using the Atkinson cycle provides good fuel efficiency, it is at the expense of a lower power-per-displacement as compared to a traditional four-stroke engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] If demand for more power is intermittent, the power of the engine can be supplemented by an electric motor during times when more power is needed.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This forms the basis of an Atkinson cycle-based hybrid electric drivetrain.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] These electric motors can be used independently of, or in combination with, the Atkinson-cycle engine, to provide the most efficient means of producing the desired power.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This drive-train first entered production in late 1997 in the first-generation Toyota Prius.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The 1887 patent (US 367496) describes the mechanical linkages necessary to obtain all four strokes of the four-stroke cycle for a gas engine within one revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] There is also a reference to an 1886 Atkinson patent (US 336505), which describes an opposed-piston gas engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The British patent for the "Utilite'" is from 1892 (#2492).
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Colonel **Sir Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford**, FRS (26 March 1753 – 21 August 1814), was an American-born British military officer, scientist and inventor.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Born in Woburn, Massachusetts, he supported the Loyalist cause during the American War of Independence, commanding the King's American Dragoons during the conflict.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] After the war ended in 1783, Thompson moved to London, where he was recognised for his administrative talents and received a knighthood from George III in 1784.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] A prolific scientist and inventor, Thompson also created several new warship designs.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He subsequently moved to the Electorate of Bavaria and entered into the employ of the Bavarian government, heavily reorganising the Bavarian Army.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was rewarded for his efforts by being made an Imperial Count in 1792 before dying in Paris in 1814.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was born in rural Woburn, in the Province of Massachusetts Bay, on 26 March 1753; his birthplace is preserved as a museum.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He was educated mainly at the village school, although he sometimes walked almost ten miles to Cambridge with the older Loammi Baldwin to attend lectures by Professor John Winthrop of Harvard College.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] At the age of 13 he was apprenticed to John Appleton, a merchant of nearby Salem.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson excelled at his trade, and coming in contact with refined and well educated people for the first time, adopted many of their characteristics including an interest in science.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] While recuperating in Woburn in 1769 from an injury, Thompson conducted his first experiments studying the nature of heat and began to correspond with Baldwin and others about them.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Later that year he worked several months for a Boston shopkeeper and then apprenticed himself briefly, and unsuccessfully, to a doctor in Woburn.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson's prospects were dim in 1772 but in that year they changed abruptly.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He met, charmed and married a rich and well-connected widow, an heiress named Sarah Rolfe (née Walker).
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Her father was a minister, and her late husband left her property at Rumford, Province of New Hampshire, which is today in the modern city of Concord.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] They moved to Portsmouth, and through his wife's influence with the governor, he was appointed a major in the New Hampshire Militia.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Their child (also named Sarah) was born in 1774.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Following the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War in 1775, Thompson, by now a wealthy and influential landowner, came out as a Loyalist.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He was soon using his connections in the colonial militia to recruit and arm Loyalists seeking to fight alongside the British against rebel forces, which earned him the enmity of Patriots in New Hampshire.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was stripped of his militia commission and a Patriot mob attacked and burned down his house, causing him to flee to British lines, abandoning his wife in the process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He became a political and military advisor to General Thomas Gage (to whom Thompson was already passing information on Patriots), and later assisted Lord George Germain in organizing and provisioning Loyalist military units.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1781, Thompson raised his own military unit, the King's American Dragoons, which was primarily stationed on Long Island in 1782 and early 1783, where they became notorious for demolishing a church and burial ground in order to erect Fort Golgotha in Huntington, New York.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] During his military career, Thompson conducted experiments to measure the force of gunpowder, the results of which were widely acclaimed when published in 1781 in the *Philosophical Transactions* of the Royal Society.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1779, he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society In 1780 Thompson was appointed as Under-Secretary of the Northern Department in the British Government.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] But he left abruptly in the following year and traveled to North America as Lieutenant Colonel of the King's American Dragoons.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] When the American Revolutionary War came to an end, he returned to England and successfully applied to become full colonel.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1783 he had a portrait painted of himself by Thomas Gainsborough, which is now on display in the Fogg Art Museum.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] On 23 February 1784, George III conferred upon him the honor of knighthood.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1785, he moved to Bavaria where he became an *aide-de-camp* to the Prince-elector Charles Theodore.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He spent eleven years in Bavaria, reorganizing the army and establishing workhouses for the poor.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He also invented Rumford's Soup, a soup for the poor, and established the cultivation of the potato in Bavaria.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He studied methods of cooking, heating, and lighting, including the relative costs and efficiencies of wax candles, tallow candles, and oil lamps.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] On Prince Charles' behalf he created the Englischer Garten in Munich in 1789; it remains today and is known as one of the largest urban public parks in the world.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1789.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] For his efforts, in 1791 Thompson was made an Imperial Count, becoming *Reichsgraf von Rumford*.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He took the name "Rumford" after the town of Rumford, New Hampshire, which was an older name for Concord where he had been married.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His experiments on gunnery and explosives led to an interest in heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He devised a method for measuring the specific heat of a solid substance but was disappointed when Johan Wilcke published his parallel discovery first.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson next investigated the insulating properties of various materials, including fur, wool and feathers.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He correctly deduced that the insulating properties of these natural materials arise from the fact that they inhibit the convection of air.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He then inferred — incorrectly — that air and, in fact, all gases, were perfect non-conductors of heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He further saw this as evidence of the argument from design, contending that divine providence had arranged for fur on animals in such a way as to guarantee their comfort.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1797, he extended his claim about non-conductivity to liquids.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The idea raised considerable objections from the scientific establishment, John Dalton and John Leslie making particularly forthright attacks.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Instrumentation far exceeding anything available in terms of accuracy and precision would have been needed to verify Thompson's claim.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Again, he seems to have been influenced by his theological beliefs, and historian of science D.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Cardwell speculated that Thompson wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He is considered the founder of the sous-vide food preparation method owing to his experiment with a mutton shoulder.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He described this method in one of his essays.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford's most important scientific work took place in Munich, and centred on the nature of heat, which he contended in "An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction" (1798) was not the caloric of then-current scientific thinking but a form of *motion*.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring cannon at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford immersed a cannon barrel in water and arranged for a specially blunted boring tool.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He showed that the water could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Though this work met with a hostile reception, it was subsequently important in establishing the laws of conservation of energy later in the 19th century.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He explained Pictet's experiment, which demonstrates the reflection of cold, by supposing that all bodies emit invisible rays, undulations in the ethereal fluid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He did experiments to support his theories of calorific and frigorific radiation and said the communication of heat was the net effect of calorific (hot) rays and frigorific (cold) rays and the rays emitted by the object.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] When an object absorbs radiation from a warmer object (calorific rays) its temperature rises, and when it absorbs radiation from a colder object (frigorific rays) its temperature falls.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] See note 8, "An enquiry concerning the nature of heat and the mode of its communication" Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, starting at page 112.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was an active and prolific inventor, developing improvements for chimneys, fireplaces and industrial furnaces, as well as inventing a double boiler, a kitchen range, and a coffee drip-press pot roughly between 1810 and 1814.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He invented a percolating coffee pot following his pioneering work with the Bavarian Army, where he improved the diet of the soldiers (Rumford's Soup) as well as their clothes.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The Rumford fireplace created a sensation in London when he introduced the idea of restricting the chimney opening to increase the updraught, which was a much more efficient way to heat a room than earlier fireplaces.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He and his workers modified fireplaces by inserting bricks into the hearth to make the side walls angled, and added a choke to the chimney to increase the speed of air going up the flue.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The effect was to produce a streamlined air flow, so all the smoke would go up into the chimney rather than lingering and entering the room.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] It also had the effect of increasing the efficiency of the fire, and gave extra control of the rate of combustion of the fuel, whether wood or coal.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Many fashionable London houses were modified to his instructions, and became smoke-free.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thomas Jefferson used the Rumford fireplace design at Monticello.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson became a celebrity when news of his success spread.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His work was also very profitable, and much imitated when he published his analysis of the way chimneys worked.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In many ways, he was similar to Benjamin Franklin, who also invented a new kind of heating stove.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The retention of heat was a recurring theme in his work, as he is also credited with the invention of thermal underwear.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson also significantly improved the design of kilns used to produce quicklime, and Rumford furnaces were soon being constructed throughout Europe.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The key innovation involved separating the burning fuel from the limestone, so that the lime produced by the heat of the furnace was not contaminated by ash from the fire.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford worked in photometry, the measurement of light.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He made a photometer and introduced the standard candle, the predecessor of the candela, as a unit of luminous intensity.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His standard candle was made from the oil of a sperm whale, to rigid specifications.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He also published studies of "illusory" or subjective complementary colours, induced by the shadows created by two lights, one white and one coloured; these observations were cited and generalized by Michel-Eugène Chevreul as his "law of simultaneous colour contrast" in 1839.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] After 1799, he divided his time between France and England.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] With Sir Joseph Banks, he established the Royal Institution of Great Britain in 1799.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The pair chose Sir Humphry Davy as the first lecturer.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The institution flourished and became world-famous as a result of Davy's pioneering research.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His assistant, Michael Faraday, established the Institution as a premier research laboratory, and also justly famous for its series of public lectures popularizing science.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] That tradition continues to the present, and the Royal Institution Christmas lectures attract large audiences through their TV broadcasts.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson endowed the Rumford medals of the Royal Society and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and endowed the Rumford Chair of Physics at Harvard University.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1803, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1772, Thompson married a rich and well-connected widow, an heiress named Sarah Rolfe (née Walker).
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson abandoned his American wife, Sarah, at the outbreak of the American Revolution; she died in 1792.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] After several affairs and a close friendship with Lady Emily (Amelia) Mary Lamb Temple (21 April 1787...11 September 1869), Viscountess Palmerston,(born Mary Mee), in 1804, he married Marie-Anne Lavoisier, the widow of the great French chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson separated from his second wife after three years, but he settled in Paris and continued his scientific work until his death on 21 August 1814.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson is buried in the small cemetery of Auteuil in Paris, just across from Adrien-Marie Legendre.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Upon his death, his daughter from his first marriage, Sarah Thompson, inherited his title as Countess Rumford.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Some periodicals and satirical publications of Rumford’s time made references that associated him with men who were publicly linked to homosexuality, notably George Germain, 1st Viscount Sackville..
[src:atkinson-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford’s surviving letters and papers do not contain evidence of same-sex relationships, and no independent contemporary documentation corroborates the claims.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Born in Paris, Clapeyron studied at the École polytechnique, graduating in 1818.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] In 1820 he and Gabriel Lamé went to Saint Petersburg to teach and work at the school of public works there.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] He returned to Paris only after the Revolution of July 1830, supervising the construction of the first railway lines connecting Paris to Versailles and Paris to Saint-Germain.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] The half brothers Stéphane Mony and Eugène Flachat collaborated in this project, which was financed by Adolphe d'Eichthal(fr), Rothschild, Auguste Thurneyssen, Sanson Davillier and the Péreire brothers.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron took his steam engine designs to England in 1836 to find a manufacturer and engaged Sharp, Roberts and Co.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] From 1844 to 1859 Clapeyron was a professor at École des Ponts et Chaussées.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron married Mélanie Bazaine, daughter of Pierre-Dominique Bazaine (mathematician and ingénieur des ponts), and older sister of Pierre-Dominique (Adolphe) Bazaine (railway engineer) and François Achille Bazaine (Marshal of France).
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Though Carnot had developed a compelling analysis of a generalised heat engine, he had employed the clumsy and already unfashionable caloric theory.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron, in his memoire, presented Carnot's work in a more accessible and analytic graphical form, showing the Carnot cycle as a closed curve on an indicator diagram, a chart of pressure against volume (named in his honor **Clapeyron's graph**).
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron's analysis of Carnot was more broadly disseminated in 1843 when Johann Poggendorff translated it into German.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] These foundations enabled him to make substantive extensions of Clausius' work, including the formula, now known as the Clausius–Clapeyron relation, which characterises the phase transition between two phases of matter.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] He further considered questions of phase transitions in what later became known as Stefan problems.
[src:atkinson-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron also worked on the characterisation of perfect gases, the equilibrium of homogeneous solids, and calculations of the statics of continuous beams, notably the theorem of three moments (**Clapeyron's theorem**).
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The **Brayton cycle**, also known as the **Joule cycle**, is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the operation of certain heat engines that have air or some other gas as their working fluid.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] It is characterized by isentropic compression and expansion, and isobaric heat addition and rejection, though practical engines have adiabatic rather than isentropic steps.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The most common current application is in airbreathing jet engines and gas turbine engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The engine cycle is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer, who developed the Brayton Ready Motor in 1872, using a piston compressor and piston expander.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] An engine using the cycle was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791, using a reciprocating compressor and a turbine expander.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] There are two main types of Brayton cycles: closed and open.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In a closed cycle, the working gas stays inside the engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Heat is introduced with a heat exchanger or external combustion and expelled with a heat exchanger.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] With the open cycle, air from the atmosphere is drawn in, goes through three steps of the cycle, and is expelled again to the atmosphere.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Open cycles allow for internal combustion.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Although the cycle is open, it is conventionally assumed for the purposes of thermodynamic analysis that the exhaust gases are reused in the intake, enabling analysis as a closed cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1872, George Brayton applied for a patent for his "Ready Motor", a reciprocating heat engine operating on a gas power cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The engine was a two-stroke and produced power on every revolution.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton engines used a separate piston compressor and piston expander, with compressed air heated by internal fire as it entered the expander cylinder.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The first versions of the Brayton engine were vapor engines which mixed fuel with air as it entered the compressor; town gas was used or a surface carburetor was also used for mobile operation .
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The fuel / air was contained in a reservoir / tank and then it was admitted to the expansion cylinder and burned.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] As the fuel/air mixture entered the expansion cylinder, it was ignited by a pilot flame.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A screen was used to prevent the fire from entering or returning to the reservoir.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In early versions of the engine, this screen sometimes failed and an explosion would occur.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1874, Brayton solved the explosion problem by adding the fuel just prior to the expander cylinder.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The engine now used heavier fuels such as kerosene and fuel oil.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton produced and sold "Ready Motors" to perform a variety of tasks like water pumping, mill operation, running generators, and marine propulsion.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The "Ready Motors" were produced from 1872 to sometime in the 1880s; several hundred such motors were likely produced during this time period.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton licensed the design to Simone in the UK.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Many variations of the layout were used; some were single-acting and some were double-acting.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Some had under walking beams; others had overhead walking beams.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Both horizontal and vertical models were built.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Sizes ranged from less than one to over 40 horsepower.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Critics of the time claimed the engines ran smoothly and had a reasonable efficiency.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton-cycle engines were some of the first internal combustion engines used for motive power.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1875, John Holland used a Brayton engine to power the world's first self-propelled submarine (Holland boat #1).
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1879, a Brayton engine was used to power a second submarine, the *Fenian Ram*.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] John Philip Holland's submarines are preserved in the Paterson Museum in the Old Great Falls Historic District of Paterson, New Jersey.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Selden patented the first internal combustion automobile.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Inspired by the internal combustion engine invented by Brayton displayed at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876, Selden patented a four-wheel car working on a smaller, lighter, multicylinder version.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] He then filed a series of amendments to his application which stretched out the legal process, resulting in a delay of 16 years before the patent was granted on November 5, 1895.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1903, Selden sued Ford for patent infringement and Henry Ford fought the Selden patent until 1911.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Selden had never actually produced a working car, so during the trial, two machines were constructed according to the patent drawings.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Ford argued his cars used the four-stroke Alphonse Beau de Rochas cycle or Otto cycle and not the Brayton-cycle engine used in the Selden auto.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Ford won the appeal of the original case.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1887, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke direct-injection oil engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The fuel system used a variable-quantity pump and liquid-fuel, high-pressure, spray-type injection.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The liquid was forced through a spring-loaded, relief-type valve (injector) which caused the fuel to become divided into small droplets.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Injection was timed to occur at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A platinum igniter provided the source of ignition.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In this manner, the engine fired on every power stroke and speed and output were controlled solely by the quantity of fuel injected.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1890, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke, air-blast oil engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The fuel system delivered a variable quantity of vaporized fuel to the center of the cylinder under pressure at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The ignition source was an igniter made from platinum wire.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A variable-quantity injection pump provided the fuel to an injector where it was mixed with air as it entered the cylinder.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A small crank-driven compressor provided the source for air.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] This engine also used the lean-burn system.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Rudolf Diesel originally proposed a very high compression, constant-temperature cycle where the heat of compression would exceed the heat of combustion, but after several years of experiments, he realized that the constant-temperature cycle would not work in a piston engine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Early Diesel engines use an air blast system which was pioneered by Brayton in 1890.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Consequently, these early engines use the constant-pressure cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A Brayton-type engine consists of three components: a compressor, a mixing chamber, and an expander.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Modern Brayton engines are almost always a turbine type, although Brayton only made piston engines.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In the original 19th-century Brayton engine, ambient air is drawn into a piston compressor, where it is compressed; ideally an isentropic process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The compressed air then passes through a mixing chamber where fuel is added, an isobaric process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The pressurized air and fuel mixture is then ignited in an expansion cylinder and energy is released, causing the heated air and combustion products to expand through a piston/cylinder, another ideally isentropic process.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Some of the work extracted by the piston/cylinder is used to drive the compressor through a crankshaft arrangement.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Gas turbine engines are also Brayton engines, with three components: an air compressor, a combustion chamber, and a gas turbine.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] 2. isobaric process – the compressed air then passes through a combustion chamber, where fuel is burned, heating that air—a constant-pressure process, since the chamber is open to flow in and out.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] 3. isentropic process – the heated, pressurized air then gives up its energy, expanding through a turbine (or series of turbines).
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Some of the work extracted by the turbine is used to drive the compressor.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] 4. isobaric process – heat rejection (in the atmosphere).
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Since neither the compression nor the expansion can be truly isentropic, losses through the compressor and the expander represent sources of inescapable working inefficiencies.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In general, increasing the compression ratio is the most direct way to increase the overall power output of a Brayton system.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Figure 1 indicates how the cycle efficiency changes with an increase in pressure ratio.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Figure 2 indicates how the specific power output changes with an increase in the gas turbine inlet temperature for two different pressure ratio values.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The highest gas temperature in the cycle occurs where work transfer to the high pressure turbine (rotor inlet) takes place.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] This is lower than the highest gas temperature in the engine (combustion zone).
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The maximum cycle temperature is limited by the turbine materials and required turbine life.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] This also limits the pressure ratios that can be used in the cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] For a fixed-turbine inlet temperature, the net work output per cycle increases with the pressure ratio (thus the thermal efficiency) and the net work output.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] With less work output per cycle, a larger mass flow rate (thus a larger system) is needed to maintain the same power output, which may not be economical.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In most common designs, the pressure ratio of a gas turbine ranges from about 11 to 16.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A closed Brayton cycle recirculates the working fluid; the air expelled from the turbine is reintroduced into the compressor, this cycle uses a heat exchanger to heat the working fluid instead of an internal combustion chamber.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The closed Brayton cycle is used, for example, in closed-cycle gas turbines for power generation in space.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 2002, a hybrid open solar Brayton cycle was operated for the first time consistently and effectively with relevant papers published, in the frame of the EU SOLGATE program.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The air was heated from 570 to over 1000K into the combustor chamber.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Further hybridization was achieved during the EU Solhyco project running a hybridized Brayton cycle with solar energy and biodiesel only.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] This technology was scaled up to 4.6 MW within the project Solugas located near Seville, where it is currently demonstrated at precommercial scale.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] A Brayton cycle that is driven in reverse uses work to move heat.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] This makes it a form of gas refrigeration cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] When air is the working fluid, it is known as the Bell Coleman cycle.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] It is also used in the LNG industry for subcooling LNG using power from a gas turbine to drive the compressor.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] This is an open Brayton cycle which also generates work from heat, but with a different order of the stages.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] Incoming air is first heated at atmospheric pressure, and then passes through the turbine, generating work.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The gas, now at a pressure lower than atmospheric, is cooled in a heat exchanger.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] The compressor raises the pressure again so the gas can be expelled to the atmosphere.
[src:atkinson-cycle/brayton-cycle] NASA is considering the Brayton cycle for its lunar nuclear reactor to be launched in 2030.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] In thermodynamics, **Bridgman's thermodynamic equations** are a basic set of thermodynamic equations, derived using a method of generating multiple thermodynamic identities involving a number of thermodynamic quantities.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] The equations are named after the American physicist Percy Williams Bridgman.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] (See also the exact differential article for general differential relationships).
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] The extensive variables of the system are fundamental.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] Only the entropy *S* , the volume *V* and the four most common thermodynamic potentials will be considered.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] The first derivatives of the internal energy with respect to its (extensive) natural variables *S* and *V* yields the intensive parameters of the system - The pressure *P* and the temperature *T* .
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] Bridgman's equations are a series of relationships between all of the above quantities.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] Many thermodynamic equations are expressed in terms of partial derivatives.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] which is the partial derivative of the enthalpy with respect to temperature while holding pressure constant.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] This method of rewriting the partial derivative was described by Bridgman (and also Lewis & Randall), and allows the use of the following collection of expressions to express many thermodynamic equations.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] Dividing, we recover the proper expression for CP.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] The following summary restates various partial terms in terms of the thermodynamic potentials, the state parameters S, T, P, V, and the following three material properties which are easily measured experimentally.
[src:atkinson-cycle/bridgman-s-thermodynamic-equations] Note that Lewis and Randall use F and E for the Gibbs energy and internal energy, respectively, rather than G and U which are used in this article.
